Very difficult. Often requiring several trips in and out. 

If a route 100‚Äô had about 10 bolts, plus an anchor to get back down (standard in a lot of areas, height dependent). That might weigh 10-15 pounds (I‚Äôm estimating, and don‚Äôt have a scale with me to verify). Add on top of that your personal gear, your ropes, your drill, batteries, water, and snacks... now carry hardware for multiple routes on top of that. We‚Äôre taking a 70-100 lb load. 

I will say: most routes ‚Äòthese days‚Äô are rap-bolted. Which is to say the hardware is installed on rappel. So you hike/climb to your access point and either haul your gear up or bring it on the hike, then rappel down to install. 

This saves on effort as you are use gravity to go down rather than fighting gravity the whole way up. It also gives you more time and intention to pick an ideal location for gear, test the rock (we tap it with a hammer, and listen to it), make sure it‚Äôs in line with the route and ‚Äòout of the way‚Äô or in a convenient place to clip from. 

The days of ground-up bolting aren‚Äôt gone, but its rare and often done by those in the cutting edge and fringe of climbing where access/time/resources are limited or legislation dictates ‚Äòno power tools‚Äô.
I appreciate that, I was covering my bases so as to not make assumptions. Cheers.

And you may have heard them correctly.... though I‚Äôd be concerned if that‚Äôs their approach. There was a short period where folks were doing that, and then some brilliant engineers tested it and proved that it reduces their holding strength in all cases.
Happy to share some insight.

Sabotage has happened, however is by no means common. It used to happen ‚Äòback in the day‚Äô in places and was made infamous between some very prominent climbers of the early years. 

It continues to happen now, but not for the reasons you might think. ‚ÄòSabotage‚Äô as it happens  right now is mostly due to overinflated egos and folks taking the position: ‚Äúwhen I climbed it back when dinosaurs roamed, we only had 2 bolts for the whole route‚Äù and will chop and ‚Äòretro-bolting‚Äô that alters the ‚Äòoriginal route‚Äô often in the quest for increased safety. 

I have an opinion on this, but generally try and stay out of it as it often becomes a pissing match between ‚Äòsafety‚Äô and ‚Äòlegacy‚Äô, and ultimately sours the community. 

Often you can‚Äôt know who put bolts in, and it is up to the individual to choose to climb something or not. You have to be accountable for your own choices, is my personal philosophy.

I never said they never fail, if someone above claimed that, they are likely overstating. 

That being said, the correct hardware on the correct environment may last longer than we live, but gear is at best as good/strong as the rock you put it in. 

To answer your other question, older hardware 70s-90s era was steel rather than stainless and often ‚Äútoo small‚Äù by contemporary standards. A lot of folks use 3/8‚Äù-1/2‚Äù diameter bolts these days whereas some older gear is often 1/4‚Äù And have rusted beyond the point of even ‚Äúmarginal security‚Äù. 

Also, as folks fall on bolts they flex and can expand the holes they‚Äôre in over years. Add on top of that potential for water, freeze/thaw cycles, and galvanic corrosion (metal-on-metal electrolysis (my science is off, but look it up)) these things have a working life.

Great question! Let me know if I can answer anything else.

There are 2 types, they use both. They do not combine epoxy and expansion bolts. 

Drill a hole:
Option one: a ‚Äúglue in‚Äù which uses epoxy. 
Option two: an expansion bolt which takes a wrench (ideally with a torque wrench  so it‚Äôs tightened to spec.). 

There is no option three where you use epoxy and an expansion bolt‚Äîto do so increases the likelihood of failure. It has been tested.

Edit: can‚Äôt find source... I used to work as a professional climbing guide and volunteered in local rebolting efforts: its hard work.

I can remember anger, and manifest those emotions and physical sensations in my body with effort and concentration. Same with sadness, grief, fear, confusion, anxiety, etc. 

I know I‚Äôve been happy/exited/joyous before, but I can‚Äôt simulate/recreate/manifest those feelings or physical sensations like I can with the others. I can‚Äôt even describe what they feel like... but I‚Äôve had them. I know I‚Äôve had those feelings and experienced them, but their memory is like a blank page in a book. 

Then ask me: ‚Äúwhen was the last time you felt happy?‚Äù I can‚Äôt answer that. 

Ask me when was the last time I felt angry, and I can tell you, and recall it and be just as angry/sad/disappointed/scared. 

My hope for you is that joy is in there somewhere, even if it‚Äôs masked behind many other feelings/memories. 

I can‚Äôt say we‚Äôre having the same experiences, or sharing the same journey, this is where I am and I hope it‚Äôs relatable to you in some small way.

Just a lucky bounce I guess... I‚Äôm pretty sure it broke in the first 5 feet of falling as I struck a ledge when gear pulled out of the wall (very odd circumstances, that were the culmination of a series of informed but still poor choices).

Hitting the ledge sent me into a somersault motion where I was tumbling backwards 2.5 rotations over the 40 foot drop where I struck the very steep hillside with my left ear and shoulder first (I had dirt impacted into my ear), where I proceeded to tumble/roll another 20-30 feet or so before the rope went tight. 

I needed stitches in my shin from a gash I picked up from a sharp rock in my tumble after hitting the ground, and a boot for 6 weeks while my talar process reattached itself.

One of those times where you go ‚Äúhuh, that was lucky/miraculous/crazy/stupid/adventurous/potentially-lethal/silly/dumb/miscalculated/amazing/wild‚Äù.

It aches sometimes when it‚Äôs cold out, and is a constant reminder to think through ‚Äúwhat happens if....‚Äù before acting.

They told me this after a climbing accident where I fell more than 40 feet, landed on my head, and broke my ankle. 

True story. True wisdom.
